Title: Move on Up - Single Edit
Comment:
Already submitted a different song, but my playlist of favorites kept going and once this one hit, just pure joy and vibes injected straight into my veins.

The bongos on this are killer, the horns are legendary, the voice is a beauty.

Had the pleasure of seeing The Roots play this one live once, and it was a blast.

Title: Vacation
Comment: Tried to come as close to the pin as I could. A bop that comes in at 2:59

Title: Skinnydipped
Comment: Have enjoyed this song for a while, it’s an easy listen. I don’t think we’ve seen banks in this game yet either

Title: Fell In Love With a Girl
Comment: Under 3 is easy, let's go under 2 minutes

Title: Tea For The Tillerman
Comment: Any fans of Extras will enjoy this. Very short song but truly terrific!

Title: Bring Night
Comment:
Before she was swinging from chandeliers or storming the stage at survivor finales, Sia was pumping out killer tracks like this one. This whole album is great but Bring Night might be my favourite. 

Nick Valensi of The Strokes was on guitar for every song on the album and developed all of the guitar parts with Sia. This song isn’t super guitar-heavy but I think you can hear some of his influence here.

Title: In The Middle
Comment: Just under the radar (2:59. I hope!). Collab between 2 great artists, one of which we have heard before in the wedding round and one is a newbie to ML. This songs kicks ass.

Title: A-Punk
Comment: This song packs such a huge punch in under 3 minutes. That opening guitar riff is super catchy and recognizable, and it’s got perfect energy fit into only a couple of minutes. And the musical interludes at 40 seconds and 1:35 are perfect for slowing the song down a bit and resetting it. This song doesn’t waste a second.

Title: Crickets
Comment:
This is an obviously good toe tapper!

Had this one sitting in my own waiting room and waiting for the right category.

Title: Pain For Pleasure
Comment:
Terrible luck that Fat Lip was submitted last round, but I swear I would have submitted this song anyway.

Sum 41 as a gag used to (maybe still does) perform as “Pain for Pleasure”, their alter-ego heavy metal band during live shows.

While this track is technically not a serious Sum 41 song, the riffs are awesome, including the first minute build-up, and I always wished they had stretched it out into a full-length single.

Title: Peaches
Album: The Presidents of The United States of America: Ten Year Super Bonus Special Anniversary Edition
Artist(s): The Presidents Of The United States Of America
Comment: 90's post grunge classic. This is going to get stuck in your head, and you can thank me for that later.

Title: Half of forever
Comment: Wanted to submit this song for other rounds but it works here, clocking in at just 2:33. Henrik is a dude from New Jersey, not Sweden.

Title: Ok Love You Bye
Comment: I love Olivia Dean and have been trying to find a category to fit her and this one gets under the wire. I love how the British accent comes through.

Title: When Worlds Collide
Comment:
"You're killing independent George!"

(This one has an amazing music video if you're at all interested: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lsV500W4BHU)

Title: Vicious
Comment: Clocking in at 2:30. I miss old Sabrina! She had such a fun sound in this era.

Title: Take It Off
Comment: Good girl rock song. Reminds me of high school (this was my fourth choice!)

Title: You're Gonna Go Far, Kid
Album: Rise And Fall, Rage And Grace
Comment: I think I first heard this song (or at least the clean version) at a basketball practice, my coach was obsessed with The Offspring. Part of what helped to develop my own taste in music was hearing this song and being somewhat wowed by the sound, much different than the music my parents listened to and more in line with what I found enjoyable. Pretty crazy they've been around since the mid-80s and their most-streamed hit came out so recently.

Title: Walking with a Ghost
Comment: It's been quite awhile for a T&S song, time for someone to bring them back.

Title: my ex's best friend (with blackbear)
Comment: Not a huge MGK fan but this song is a banger

Title: Take Me or Leave Me
Comment: If you haven't read the story of Jonathan Larson the writer of Rent, it's sooo sad. But he was a very young talent in the musical world and Rent was a phenomenon but he died at 35 the night that it premiered off broadway. So he never got to see the success of the musical. This is my favourite song from the musical. It’s got great harmonies and Idina Menzel is an icon and this is what kicked off her career. She’s the Queen of Broadway and this song shows it off.

Title: Theme From New York, New York - 2008 Remastered
Comment:
Springfield, Springfield! 

If we're doing a musicals round, I'm going with an all-time classic.

Title: You Cut Up The Clothes In The Closet Of My Dreams
Comment: Beautiful and inspiring

Title: A Million Dreams
Album: The Greatest Showman (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)
Artist(s): Ziv Zaifman, Hugh Jackman, Michelle Williams
Comment: Beautiful song from an excellent movie. The song was also covered by Pink but I like the original a little better anyway. If you haven’t seen it, highly recommend.

Title: Screech In
Album: Come From Away (Original Broadway Cast Recording)
Comment: Pure joy. For the uninitiated, Come From Away is about 9/11 and the passengers on the hundred plus planes that got stranded in a little village in Newfoundland because of all the airspace closures. This song sees some of the characters out at a tavern and going through the initiation of becoming Newfoundlanders. It's low stakes but extremely fun.

Title: Candy Store
Album: Heathers: The Musical (World Premiere Cast Recording)
Artist(s): Jessica Keenan Wynn, Alice Lee, Elle McLemore
Comment: The Wikiedpia synopsis for Heathers reads like an acid trip (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heathers:_The_Musical). Caught this song in my YouTube suggestions about a decade ago now, quite the hook and delivers all the way through.

Title: Superstar
Artist(s): Murray Head, Andrew Lloyd Webber, Tim Rice, The Trinidad Singers
Comment: I watched the live John Legend Jesus Christ Superstar because this song is a banger and I thought it was in the beginning so I was like “ok I’ll watch until they sing it” but then it turned out it was like the last song? As a Jew, I have to admit this goes so hard. I also like when they keep singing various JCS songs in Transparent.

Title: Mustang Sally
Comment:
The Commitments was one of my mom's favorite movies, and she always had the soundtrack on.

When researching this, I found out that the actor who is signing this version of the song was only 16 at the time of filming, pretty incredible voice especially at that age.

Also discovered that they did turn this into a live stage play after, so it's both screen and stage for any sticklers (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Commitments_(musical))

Title: Always Remember Us This Way
Album: A Star Is Born Soundtrack (Without Dialogue)
Comment:
I got the warning that someone also posted Lady Gaga, which only confirms this choice for two big reasons: 

1. We agree that A Star is Born is a musical. 

2. They probably submitted Shallow, which is so good and mainstream that it makes all the other songs underrated, especially this one!!

My first bartending job was at a 1 screen theater and we sold out this film for 3 months. Every time, over half the audience had some form of tears flowing as the lights came on.

Title: Shallow
Comment: This movie was decently big but I feel is pretty forgotten now… bringing it back

Title: Put on Your Sunday Clothes
Artist(s): Gavin Creel, Taylor Trensch, Bette Midler, Will Burton, Melanie Moore, Hello, Dolly! Ensemble (2017)
Comment: First and foremost, RIP Gavin Creel. This song is an absolute mood booster for me. One of my favorites from a show full of absolute bangers.

Title: This Is Me
Album: The Greatest Showman (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)
Artist(s): Keala Settle, The Greatest Showman Ensemble
Comment: When I think about the great musical / broadway song, I’m looking for something that works anywhere - in a movie, on stage, listening at home, in the car, etc. This song is great anywhere. Incredible lyrics about self acceptance. And also that huge, cinematic sound mixed with powerful vocals.

Title: Act One Finale
Album: Urinetown The Musical (Original Broadway Cast Recording)
Comment: This is a very quirky musical. About a town where the mayor has put a charge on all public bathrooms. To which the crowd rebel against and start a Les Mes - esque revolution against. Its one of the best musicals I have seen that I wasnt expecting much from and recommend it to anyone if you notice an upcoming production.

Title: Magic Dance
Album: Labyrinth (From The Original Soundtrack Of The Jim Henson Film)
Comment:
'You remind me of the babe (what babe?)
Babe with the power (what power?)
Power of voodoo (who do?)
You do (do what?)
Remind me of the babe'

Going outside the box a bit here. Labyrinth ("a 1986 musical fantasy film directed by Jim Henson from a screenplay by Terry Jones") was my favourite movie as a child, so if you downvote you are spitting on my childhood memories. Plus David Bowie as the Goblin King rules.

Video clip is way better if you want to see Bowie as the Goblin King tossing around puppet goblins while an adorable baby laughs https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xBv4Ne67QcM 

And some fun Labyrinth facts because why not:

*The "Dance Magic" scene consisted of over 48 puppets, 52 puppeteers, and eight people in goblin costumes

*Michael Jackson, Prince, and Mick Jagger were considered to play Goblin King Jareth. Jim Henson preferred Sting, until his kids convinced him that David Bowie would be best suited to it.

Title: Sincerely, Me
Album: Dear Evan Hansen (Original Broadway Cast Recording)
Artist(s): Mike Faist, Ben Platt, Will Roland
Comment: Haven’t actually seen this musical. I know of at least two more popular (and perhaps better) songs from this musical, but I wanted to go a little off the radar at least. This song is funny but still mostly serious to be enjoyable

Title: Popular - From "Wicked" Original Broadway Cast Recording/2003
Album: Wicked (Original Broadway Cast Recording / Deluxe Edition)
Artist(s): Stephen Schwartz, Kristin Chenoweth, Stephen Oremus
Comment:
This is the only musical I have ever seen and really enjoyed in person. Defying Gravity is the GOAT for me but 1) it is too obvious 2) when I saw it live Ana Gasteyer was the wicked witch and not Idina. So, I'll go with my second favorite song from the musical, Popular. It's just a fun song and cracks me up.

Sorry for being too cliche with this category but I sadly do not have much to work with.

Title: Rewrite The Stars
Album: The Greatest Showman (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)
Comment:
One of the last films with Efron before he got that awful plastic surgery. This is how I’ll remember him. Oh and Zendaya is beautiful too.

This track is magical, one of the best to grace the silver screen imho.

Title: Falling Slowly
Comment:
Really a category with so many worthy songs to choose from, but I'm going with this gorgeous two-parter from the 2007 Irish romantic musical drama, Once.

The harmonies (and lyrics, and music) in this song are absolutely top-notch. 

Gorgeous song and beautiful film.

Title: One Day More
Album: Les Misérables: The Motion Picture Soundtrack Deluxe (Deluxe Edition)
Comment: Les Mis is the first Broadway show I've ever seen, and I think the only show I've seen on stage multiple times. Many options from Les Misérables, but I like One Day More for this game- not super long, and too much going on to get bored.

Title: Start A Fire
Album: La La Land (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)
Comment: This is the point in La La Land where you’re supposed to be like “No! Ryan Gosling is selling out, he needs to follow his dreams!” Whereas in reality you’re thinking “wow this song is way better than anything Ryan Gosling has created, he should just tour with John Legend.”

Title: Cherry Wine - Live
Comment: Not the most upbeat song in the word but still beautiful. I love this whole album but this song is poetry. It feels like a straight up love song but is from the perspective of an abused person in a relationship. It also technically has a food and a drink in the name!

Title: Pepper
Comment: Always fun when this comes on during a mix when you are with people who have never heard of the band name before, like it did on a road trip with my wife and kids recently.

Title: Brain Stew
Comment: Questionable whether or not BRAIN stew is a food, but stew itself is certainly a food. The chord progression is iconic.

Title: You and Tequila (feat. Grace Potter)
Comment: Soft and tender song. Easy on the ears. Crazy on the tequila.

Title: Cough Syrup
Comment:
Initial somewhat related rant – I hate how many open syrups are in my fridge. We have chocolate syrup and strawberry syrup for the kids, and I see no reason they need both. Back in my day, we had one milk related syrup, and we didn’t complain about it. Then of course we have a high quality maple syrup, but then these stupid kids prefer the cheap generic sugary pancake syrup because their taste sucks. All this being said, syrup is great, but there’s a limit (and fridge space comes with opportunity costs).

In terms of the round, this song is simply incredible. I love that opening guitar, which has a bit of an ethereal feel, and the chorus absolutely rocks. I remember the first time I heard the end where the song speeds up, then slows down, then goes into full gear. Just a brilliant way to build a song.

Title: Ribs
Comment: This might be the best Lorde song overall. She was 16 when this album came out and it’s an all time favorite of mine. Even as a a teenager she understands getting old sucks. (Sorry if that clock app has taken hold of this one…)

Title: Coca Cola
Comment: Not just in the title but throughout the whole song. I like to imagine Akiva singing this as a loving tribute to Coke Zero. It’s a fun song and you should vote for it.

Title: Baguettes in the Face (feat. NAV, Playboi Carti & A Boogie Wit da Hoodie)
Artist(s): Mustard, NAV, Playboi Carti, A Boogie Wit da Hoodie
Comment: This song has everything. Mustard on the beat, NAV spitting fire, Carti speaking his own language and A Boogie is here too.

Title: Honey on My Tongue
Comment: Toes will be tapped.

Title: Honey
Comment: Any excuse to put Robyn on the playlist, I’m in. This is one of my favorites.

Title: Red Bull & Hennessy
Comment: Rilo Kiley has gotten love. But has the greatness of Jenny Lewis really been emphasized??

Title: Tangerine
Comment: Really love this beat. I’m a big fan of the group - this is not one of their most well known songs but it should be it’s totally a bop. Starts off strong as stays that way.  Saw Glass Animals in concert last year and they did not disappoint. What a trip.

Title: Waffle House
Comment: I know you’re probably dreading listening to this but it’s a pretty fun song

Title: Lollipop
Comment: This one is a tongue tapper

Title: The Blacker The Berry
Comment: My favourite from TPAB

Title: KD and Lunch Meat
Comment:
KD stands for Kraft Dinner, which is only sold in Canada. Its similar to Kraft Mac & Cheese, but different and better. Its an iconic cheap meal in Canada.

Anyways. This song is a fun little diddy.

Title: Sunday Candy
Comment:
There's so much I can say about this song, it's truly one of my all-time favorites. Is that an overused qualifier? Possibly.
But since this song was put on my radar by the teenage staff that I was managing at a summer camp 10 years ago, it's been one of the most played and most quoted songs in my house. 
It's credited as Nico Segal, who used to go by Donnie Trumpets (he changed his name after...well...*gestures around*), but this is a Chance the Rapper song first and foremost.

It's just a purely joyous song about loving your Grandma, and I can certainly relate. I have spent a decade yelling out "you sing it too, but your grandma ain't my grandma!"

Was also my gateway into Chance, who was on a total heater before completely disappearing a few years ago.

Title: Diet Pepsi
Comment: I listen to this song approximately 15 times in a row every time it comes on, it's so catchy and really sticks in my brain.

Title: Peaches En Regalia
Comment:
In 1970 this would be too obvious, but in 2025 I think this will get some love. 

No words just a colorful and joyful composition. Some say its Zappa’s best song.

Title: Orange Juice - Live From Fenway Park
Comment:
Live version is better than studio version. Not sure what this song is about, a wife that left him or something? Idk. It's a good song though. The whole Fenway album is such a banger too. Noah Kahan is great. That is all.

Honestly this round was insanely difficult. The only other song I could think of was Doses and Mimosas and I just don't think that would play well.

Title: Dance, Dance
Comment:
For Bev.
In honor of that one time he revealed to the chat that he was once a competitive Dance Dance Revolution player.

Title: Tell Me Baby
Comment:
RHCP in honour of Mr Alex Chester

I think this is a pretty well known one, but also don’t think it’s as remembered as some of their other hits

Title: Jet Lag (feat. Natasha Bedingfield)
Comment:
This one goes out to the KillerMiller to my Postman, the master of time, not the father of 32FRSFF but the father who stepped up - Mr. Av Sinensky, Esquire. 

Never in a million years did I think I’d find a song about people having miscommunications across time zones but HERE TF WE ARE!

Title: Don't Look Back in Anger - Remastered
Comment:
A favorite band of our favorite 49ers fan.

Liam Gallagher really gets to show off this vocal chops here in a way he doesn't on Wonderwall. It's a shame Oasis is known for one of their less impressive tracks musically.

Title: Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown) - Remastered 2009
Comment:
For those of you that don’t know John Barber is a big bird guy so I wanted a song with a title that referenced birds and a bird flying away is the perfect metaphor for us losing our sweet JB. 

I get the Beatles are super famous and Akiva hates them but it’s insane we haven’t had a Beatles song yet. This isnt in the top 40 most famous famous Beatles songs but I love the Sitar and the lyrics. I think Blackbird being the other Beatles song is too on the nose and too famous and I prefer this anyways.

Title: Forever In Blue Jeans
Comment: Dedicated to Evan Jean because hes the person who gave me my first ever upvote.

Title: 46 and 2
Comment:
I think Jim Crumley would appreciate the inclusion of a Tool song, I don't think we've had one yet.

Buuut, to be less bro'y, I'm going to use this fun cover by a bunch of kids via a non-profit music foundation, so your click is a charitable donation - "We know what it’s like to dream of creating music but not have the means—lessons, instruments, even access to a studio felt out of reach. That’s why OMF is, and always will be, 100% free. Money should never stand in the way of great art." - https://okmusicfoundation.org/ 

A pre-teen girl covering Maynard should never work, but she kills this song. 

Highly recommend the video so you can see how young and talented these kiddos are https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mYKLvYGqaC0 (the kid passionately banging sticks together is the real MVP)

Title: Never Forget You (feat. John Legend)
Comment: Studied some tape on Chester and learned he never forgets the five best players in the 2000 NBA Finals and which Super Bowl he fell asleep to. So I am submitting Never Forget You, with the you being sports minutiae.

Title: Out of My League
Album: More Than Just a Dream (Deluxe Edition)
Comment:
This song is dedicated to the one and only Alexander Chester, who has officially disavowed Fantasy Football and has left our league/s for good. I love this choice to honor this development because:

1) Alex is literally out of my fantasy league
2) Alex is doing this because he feels he is above fantasy football, literally out of our league in terms being ‘too good’ to be doing something he feels is beneath him
3) This song has a joyous energy about the other person feeling that way, which is how we all feel about his choice 😊

Title: CALIFORNIA (the OC theme)
Comment: Fits the criteria for multiple fallen comrades. Also, a great TV show for fellow teenagers in the early 2000s that were just trying to chill with their GFs. Semi-decent song too. Total one hit wonder but iconic TV theme song.

Title: Bang the Drum All Day - 2015 Remaster
Album: The Ever Popular Tortured Artist Effect
Comment:
This is for Crumley, let's bang the drum lots this fall winter buddy.

(For those who don't know, this is the Packers TD song)

Title: Whirring
Comment:
Do not adjust your listening device! You did not just start listening to an episode of popular Minnesota Sports podcast, 32 Fans!
That's right, this is the one and only beloved 32F theme song, only slowed down to 1.0x(!)

In honour of our dear fallen leader and Pride enthusiast, Alex Chester, but also for our other dear fallen leader (in the sense that he used to win these games), Akiva, I present you the full and glorious experience that is Whirring.

Having never heard this in full, I had to take my wife's phone, slow the podcast down to 1x and Shazam just to find what it was called. I figured if the full song isn't great, I'll ditch it for something else.  But it's better than great. It's a non-stop banger.

AND the lyrics fit Chester perfectly:
"This much delight, *fills columns* to new heights."
"You make me sleep so badly *invisible friend*"

This song is a swelling epic, building beautifully to a crescendo of shredding madness, and I instantly loved it.

And I hope you will too.

Title: Flyover State
Comment:
This one goes out to Michael Beverage. The hero of this song is from a flyover state. Well, Michael is from West Virginia, which is considered the number 1(!) flyover state* in the country. Symmetry! 

*source:https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/2017/11/15/flyover-states/860668001/)

Title: Believe It or Not (Theme from "Greatest American Hero")
Comment:
Tribute to not one but two former Music League members and current hosts of the PPPG Seinfeld podcast - Alex Chester and Av Sinensky.

Believe it or not, they’re no longer playing with us, but instead are busy podcasting and keeping us entertained. Are they The Greatest American Heroes? That’s up to you to decide.

And you know what - it’s really not a bad song! Play it again!

And for the uninitiated, you better get on that.. https://youtu.be/ria37d9mInY?si=Dm0HSoY7iAl_FfQi

Title: Surfin' Bird - 2017 Remaster
Album: Rocket to Russia (40th Anniversary Deluxe Edition)
Comment: Many months ago Allix O submitted Surfin' Bird and PEO (pissed everyone off). Honoring his memory with a cover so I don't repeat.

Title: 2 days into college
Comment: This is for John Barber’s favorite Tik Tok’er (and Philadelphia 76er) who found this song out of obscurity and made it massive on Tik Tok. A bit cheesy but catchy as hell

Title: On Top
Comment:
In honor of our king of the charts, Alex Chester and fellow ranking enthusiast Av. 

I have such reverence for Hot Fuss. I saw The Killers at Jones Beach in 2005 with my sophomore roommate and they played the album straight through and to this day is one of my favorite concert experiences ever. On Top is one of the deeper cuts on the album, but I find it infectious and the perfect early Killers banger.

Title: Gaslighter
Comment:
This song is dedicated to basically all of the fallen comrades. Raise your hand if you have been personally gaslit by someone on the list. 

(absolute banger of a song)

Title: Michael
Comment: Dedicating this song to the great Michael Beverage. The lyrics describe how we would all react to seeing him out at the club.

Title: Wolf Like Me
Comment: This is for Chester both bc he loves the Wolves but also bc of how insatiably virile he is

Title: Truly Madly Deeply
Comment: Love this song mostly for the hooligans in the British pub singing it (https://youtu.be/ruAF71UVMTc?si=067NWIugTGrdXAe7)

Title: April Sun in Cuba
Comment: Upon researching songs from the Australian region. This one stood out. There were few more much quirkier ones I was considering too not sure how well theyd do

Title: Blood
Album: The Recordings of the Middle East
Comment:
Despite their name, The Middle East is a Queensland, Australia band.

I was originally thinking of this song for another Movie soundtrack round because this came on my radar as the absolutely perfectly placed ending song to Crazy, Stupid, Love. (Side note, this is one of, if not the greatest Rom-coms AND twist movies of the past 25 years, go see it if you haven't, it's elite.)

This band won numerous Aussie-only awards, such as Australian radio station Triple J's Unearthed Artist Of The Year Award in 2009 and the Australian Music Prize in 2011.

Title: Expert In A Dying Field
Comment: I ran into an old high school friend last year, and he introduced me to one his favorite bands, The Beths, a mostly unknown indie rock band from New Zealand. No clue how he discovered them, but I was immediately hooked. I could have gone with a dozen of their songs, but this one is such a gem. They’re masters at writing incredibly catchy songs, with killer guitar, and emotional & smart lyrics. I highly recommend a deep dive into their catalog [A couple of other to try are Future Me Hates Me and Silence is Golden].

Title: Torn
Comment:
Imbruglia was born on 4 February 1975 in Sydney. 

I always liked this song and I remember it being on the top of some lists the year it came out. 

Checked the spreadsheet and doesn't appear it's a repeat.

Title: The Show
Comment: I think this song is really cute and reminds me of moneyball as the song that his daughter performs. She’s as Aussie as it gets being born and raised there and still there to this day.

Title: Never Tear Us Apart
Comment: 80s classic. An obvious choice of an INXS song, but does obvious have to mean bad?

Title: Battle Scars (feat. Lupe Fiasco)
Comment:
I didn’t even realize he sang this song until doing my research for this round. This used to be my shit back in the day. 

You can’t hear the Australian accent in his voice, but he is one of the most Australian looking men alive imo. He also wrote most of this song which is impressive.

Title: My Kind Of Scene
Comment: Listened to this band a bunch in college, probably haven’t heard them since but they still slap!

Title: Ave Maria - The Voice Australia 2021 Performance / Live
Album: Bella Taylor Smith: The Complete Collection (The Voice Australia 2021)
Comment: Wasn't sure what to pick here, but i remembered this singer from the voice australia whose audition went pretty viral a couple years ago as one of the best in the history of The Voice. So i wanted to see if she had any good tracks on spotify, and hey, here's the audio of her audition. cover of the beyonce song. her voice is outrageously good.

Title: I Want You
Comment:
Had no idea this band was Australian. Honestly, I could not name one Australian band or artist before this exercise.

This reminds me of like a 6th grade crush or something and acting cool and in love. Idk. It's Savage Garden's best song I think?  I also think a lot of people will hate it but whatever.

Title: I Said Hi
Comment: Amy Shark is a great name for an Australian singer. It's not her real name- apparently she just liked Jaws a lot and didn't want to go by Amy Billings.

Title: You Were Right
Comment:
The opposite of Tame Impala in terms of misconception; this is a trio, not one person.

Don’t have a lot to say other than they provide great rhythms and have a huge following in the electronic music scene. This song stuck with me the first time I heard it.

Title: Meditjin
Comment:
It's no Hilltop Hoods, but Indigenous hip-hop actually slaps pretty hard. I tried to pick a song that incorporates some indigenous instrumentals and language (Yolngu).

(Decent timing, the Anniversary of the UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples is on the 13th.)

Title: Walking On A Dream
Album: Walking On A Dream (10th Anniversary Edition)
Comment: Great song from this Aussie duo.

Title: Suck on Light
Comment: Really love this song and album. Especially good for road trips

Title: WHERE DOES YOUR SPIRIT GO?
Comment:
The Kid LAROI was born in Sydney. The "LAROI" in The Kid LAROI's stage name is derived from the Kamilaroi indigenous group in Australia, which his mother is a part of. Doesn't get much more Australian than that.

Emotionally charged song about the hardships associated with loss. Most of his discography is more upbeat and pop-themed but this one sticks with me for how moving it is. When TKL performed this at Coachella in 2023 he dedicated it to his childhood friend and photographer along with Juice WRLD, who was a mentor to TKL when he first entered the music industry. Truly feel the meaning and power behind his lyrics here.

Title: Zoom
Comment: That opening guitar riff deserves a thumb on its own. Last Dinosaurs are an indie rock band from Australia that saw some medium success with their debut album which is probably in my top 5 favourite albums of all time. Zoom was I think their most song popular from that album. Again, impossible to hear that riff and not get hyped.

Title: Mind Mischief
Comment:
Tame Impala unfortunately could be viewed as too “mainstream” by music heads, and too “obvious” by MusicLeague heads. I scoured the discography to find what I thought was the right one for the group.

There’s no bad choices here in my opinion. 

Currents is one of my favorite albums, but Lonerism feels like the most pure form of Tame Impala. Dreamy vocals and the instrumentals feel tight yet loose

Title: moody
Comment: Have we had Royel Otis before? I forget. A fun Australian pop duo, this song has been stuck in my head. Just ignore the slight misogyny maybe.

Title: Storms
Comment:
I very much wish I could put this full album on the playlist, it’s a truly wonderful record. 

Back when the Thieves were a trio as opposed to a duo. Their drummer is good friends with my brother, so I was of course in on them immediately out of loyalty, but their songs and harmonies were fantastic enough that my fandom was absolutely earned.

Title: My Man on Love - Remastered
Comment:
Ridiculously beautiful. 
What a voice.
I hope you all enjoy.

Title: Fare Thee Well (Dink's Song)
Album: Inside Llewyn Davis: Original Soundtrack Recording
Comment:
Fucking awesome song from one of my favorite movies of all time. And yes I am the judge Akiva of what’s fucking awesome. Also don’t have to deal with the “is this folk” debate with this one.

There were definitely other options from this soundtrack (and we may see some of them on the playlist), but this one just hit the spot for me

Title: 5 Years Time
Album: Peaceful, The World Lays Me Down
Comment: Loved this song and NATW awhile, fell back in love with the song after hearing Mister Terrific beat some bad guy ass to it, been in constant rotation since. Thank you to James Gunn for putting me back on.

Title: Cinnamon Tree
Artist(s): Marty O'Reilly & the Old Soul Orchestra
Comment: I wanted to pick a song that had lower listens so I ended up with this one with around 6M. I love how raw and soulful his voice is. His influences are all the classic Folk classics like Guthrie. I also love the poetic nature of the lyrics singing about his late dog. “It’s not the body of the beast that holds the spirit but the spirit in itself which I adore”. Hopefully it scratches the folky itch.

Title: I Feel So Good
Comment:
Growing up, folk was the primary Genre we listened to at home. My parents were patrons of the local folk station (pre Patreon days, we were swimming in tote bags) and we used to go to a local folk/rock festival every summer. So if any motherfucker in here tells me that Canadian legend Richard Thompson is not folk, I will crash out.
This song is a bop, and has always been one of my favourite albums.

Title: Gay Pirates
Album: Is The World Strange Or Am I Strange?
Comment:
Described by the Guardian as “a folksy stomp designed to tackle homophobia by getting beered up lads to sing along before they realise what it’s about”. And the artist said he wanted to give it a “folklore thing” to make it feel embedded in history. So it’s folk!

Not sure if he solved homophobia with this song but hey it was worth a try. The artist is now an actor and he’s apparently starring in Shogun, but I haven’t gotten around to watching that yet.

There is a 4 min version and a 6 min version. I’ve tried to select the 4 min version but if I accidentally did the 6 min version I’m very sorry!

Title: Don't Think Twice, It's All Right
Comment: Not a huge Dylan fan but really liked this when I heard it in the movie.

Title: Betsy the Serving Maid
Comment:
This won't win, but I'll plug someone I grew up listening to because of my Dad. Martin Simpson is probably one of the best guitarists and folk singers in the world that no one has ever heard of. His instrumental tracks are his best work, but not suitable for this prompt.

"He has had the most nominations of any performer in the 18 years of the BBC Radio 2 Folk Awards, an astonishing 32 times, 13 of those as Musician of the Year, winning that particular accolade twice."

"He is listed in Gibson Guitars’ Top 30 Acoustic Guitarists of all time, and Acoustic Guitar readers voted him number 12 guitarist in the world in 2005."

Title: Blue Bayou
Comment:
I think there might be “country vs folk” drama here but I don’t care. All folk is country, and this is folky enough for me! A personal favorite of mine that I’ve been itching to submit

I enjoy the lyrics and relate to the feeling of longing for your place of peace. I named my boat “Blue Bayou” because well, it’s blue, and the lyrics apply to my relationship with the river. Also a great double-entendre when it comes to rowing past other people (“blew by you”)

“If I could only see that familiar sunrise through sleepy eyes, how happy I’d be”
“Some sweet day is gonna take away this hurting inside. I’ll never be blue, my dreams come true on Blue Bayou”

Title: Forest Floor
Comment: I love man/woman folk duos and ocie elliott is doing it really well these days. This is a nice one (what I say after hearing any ocie elliott song)

Title: The Pugilist
Comment: Keaton Henson is an English musician who would be in my top 5-10 artists to see live, except he suffers from severe anxiety and rarely performs live. His top three genres are folk rock, classical, and indie folk, per the internet. If you like this song, you are in for a true with his catalog.

Title: My Silver Lining
Comment: I was introduced to this duo through TML, and I really fell in love with their soulful folk style. Gorgeous harmonies and a perfectly modern foreign feel on an old genre.

Title: my tears ricochet
Comment: We haven’t gotten any Taylor through 9 series here (I think). This is my favorite track off either of the folk(ish) albums

Title: Rearview
Comment: I don’t listen to folk music in my regular life, so I put on a folk playlist on Spotify and this was the first song I liked. If you downvote this because it isn’t folk you are objectively wrong.

Title: When My Time Comes
Comment: Dawes, one of the best American folk rock bands going. Taylor goldsmith Is a great lyricist. This song killed live at folk fest last year

Title: I Believe You
Comment: Got a tip that this artist Todd Snider is a great storyteller and his songs can be quirky.

Title: Beneath Oak Trees
Comment: Gossett has a few great folk songs over the last few years. This is one of my favourites as it entrances me into the forrest when listening.

Title: Closer to Fine
Comment: Let’s go, lesbians! A classic, and for a reason.

Title: Thinking 'Bout Love
Comment:
Maybe my favorite band I came upon this year. This is their most popular song per every metric but I think it's their best also. Just a cool, chill band. Good vibes. And they are Canadian which is cool.

Shout out Caamp. They have too many songs to pick from though.
